        Boxley Materials announces sale to Denver-based business
    


By Duncan Adams
duncan.adams@roanoke.com
981-3324












Duncan Adams


























Feb 23, 2016
 (…)


























































































Homegrown Boxley Materials stands poised to join a list of other businesses once headquartered in the region that have been acquired by a company based elsewhere.Boxley Materials employs about 350 people in Virginia and said they will remain employed after the transition to a new owner.Established by the Boxley family in Roanoke in 1906, Boxley Materials announced Tuesday that it has signed an agreement to sell the company to Summit Materials, an international, publicly held company headquarter in Denver.Both companies’ product lines include ready-mixed concrete, crushed stone, concrete, asphalt and other construction materials.Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Summit reported that the Boxley acquisition and the separate acquisition of American Materials Co., announced Feb. 11, represented a combined investment of about $250 million.Boxley said it anticipates the transaction will close in mid-March. A news release from Boxley reported that Summit will retain Boxley’s leadership team, led by Ab Boxley, president and CEO of the family-owned business now based in Bedford County.Boxley Materials will keep its name.Ab Boxley declined to comment Tuesday about specific details regarding the sale, noting he was limited in what he could disclose about the deal until a regulatory review concludes.Boxley Materials reported in December that it planned to sell the company’s West Virginia group of facilities and was attracting interest also for Boxley’s Virginia-based assets.The sale of the West Virginia operations to Oldcastle Materials, based in Atlanta, closed Dec. 31.
Ab Boxley said in early December that as the construction industry rebounded from the Great Recession, some companies, included publicly traded ones, were looking to expand.At the time, he said any offers to buy Boxley Materials’ remaining assets would be judged by key criteria: that the sale will benefit the owners of Boxley Materials, that any such deal will provide opportunities for existing workers and that the buyer would offer good things for the region.On Tuesday, he said he feels comfortable that Summit will have the same commitment to community involvement and support that Boxley Materials has had.In recent decades, several Roanoke born-and-bred companies have been acquired by businesses headquartered elsewhere. They include Roanoke Electric Steel, Valley Bank, Dominion Bank, ADMMicro, HSMM and Interactive Achievement.Summit Materials’ stock trades on the New York Stock Exchange as SUM.





















































Tags


Boxley Materials


Ab Boxley


Summit Materials


Tom Hill


Denver


Ready-mixed Concrete


Admmicro














